Introduction¶

Ford, in collaboration with Motivate, is launching Ford GoBike a regional bike-share network designed to enhance sustainable transportation in the San Francisco Bay Area. Ford GoBike is the Bay Areas newest sustainable transportation option. The system will serve San Francisco, San Jose, Oakland, Berkeley and Emeryville and rapidly grow to 7,000 bikes at 546 stations by the end of 2018. The first three months of 2019 datasets were downloaded from a baywheels-data hosted on AWS(amazon web services), the three dataset will be joined together has one dataset since they are of the same structure. These datasets will be wrangled for proper exploration of the data, analysed to find patterns and trends, and visualize the insights gained through charts and graphs.

Quality Issues¶

  1. Erroneous data types: start_time,end_time,start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id

  2. Missing records in start_station_id,end_station_id,start_station_name and end_station_name

Tidiness Issues¶

Geographical area is also a factor that influences the operations of the bikeshare system, it can be useful in these case study to understand how the bikeshare system is developing in each geographical area. We can get this data by leveraging the coordinates given as attributes.

In [153]:
# using a geodesic function from the geopy library to get the distance between each start station and end station
locations = []
for row in bikeshare_clean.itertuples():
    start_station_coordinate = (row.start_station_latitude,row.start_station_longitude)
    end_station_coordinate = (row.end_station_latitude,row.end_station_longitude)
    locations.append(geodesic(start_station_coordinate,end_station_coordinate).km)
In [154]:
# creating a dataframe from the retrieved data above
bikeshare_distances = pd.DataFrame(data=locations)
bikeshare_distances.columns = ['distances(km)']

The structure of this dataset¶

The original shape of the dataset was 631793 observations and 14 attributes,but after thorough data cleaning the shape of the dataset became 482555 observations and 18 attributes due to the addition of geographical area and distance of the rides taken.

The main features of interest in this dataset¶

The features that interest me in this dataset are:

  • The duration of each rides

  • The start time of the rides and the end time of the rides

  • The type of users that use this bikeshare system

  • how customer and subscribers use the bikeshare system

  • The geographical area where the bikeshare system are operating

  • The distances covered in each rides

The features in the dataset that i think will help support my investigation into my feature(s) of interest?¶

The features in the dataset that will help support my investigations are: time(start_time and end_time),duration,distances,geographical area(neighbourhood and city) and users_types

Insights Gained During Univariate Exploration¶

  • The duration in seconds was converted to minutes in order to have an intuitive understanding of the distribution as seconds values were large and with huge margins between them. Three more attributes were created(hour,day,date) to have a broad insight on what aspect of time we more demands made.
  • Most Trips lasted not more than 15 minutes and some trips lasting more than that.
  • The demand for bikes peaked just before midweek for every month in the first quarter of the year, more indepth investigation will be taken to reveal an event that occurs at that time.
  • The demand for bikes peaked twiced each day from 8-9AM and 5-6PM, there were more trips on weekdays than weekends with the peak on Thursdays.
  • The average distance between each stations from beginning of the trip to the end was not up to 2 kilometres with user riding more than 4 kilometres away from the start station
  • The top neigbourhoods with highest demands for bikes were South beach, Union square and Civic center.
  • Market St at 10th St station is most popular station in terms of demand for bikes with close to 12,000 trips in the first quarter, it is located in a neighbourhood of Civic center and in a city of San Francisco, San Francisco seems to be the major city were Ford Gobike system is used with atleast 72% of the total trips of the Ford Gobike system in the city.
  • Subscribers are the major users of this bike system with atleast 88% of the total trips were from subscribers. Only about 8% of the total trips were from the 'BikeShare For All' program.

Insights Gained During Bivariate Exploration¶

  • Total duration can be used to aggregate how long users used the bikes for a certain period of time. There was a continuous increase in total duration of trips in each day from january to march even though there variations at certain points.
  • There were two particular hours of the day were the total duration were at peak, which are 8-9AM and 5-6PM. Commuters spent an average time of atleast 15 minutes from 12AM to 3AM and lower from at any other hour of the day.
  • The total duration of trips were higher during weekdays and the average time spent on trips were higher during weekends.
  • Subscribers had about 76% of the total duration of trips but customers had double the average time spent on trips.
  • Based on the graphs plotted above time is not a major factor that affects the distance covered by the users.
  • Customers travel a farther distance from the start station than subscribers.
  • The users of the 'BikeShare For All' program are subscribers and customers that don't use the 'BikeShare For All' program

Plot to explore the time of the day different users demand bikes¶

In [188]:
plt.suptitle('Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Customers and Subscribers')
fig,ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(14,5))
customers = bikeshare_master.query('user_type == "Customer"')
customers = customers.groupby(['start_day', 'start_hour']).size()
customers = customers.reset_index(name='count')
customers = customers.pivot(index='start_day', columns='start_hour', values='count')
sb.heatmap(customers, cmap='rocket_r',ax=ax1);
plt.title('Customer', loc='right');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');

fig,ax2 = plt.subplots(figsize=(14,5))
subscribers = bikeshare_master.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
subscribers = subscribers.groupby(['start_day', 'start_hour']).size()
subscribers = subscribers.reset_index(name='count')
subscribers = subscribers.pivot(index='start_day', columns='start_hour', values='count')
sb.heatmap(subscribers, cmap='rocket_r',ax=ax2);
plt.title('Subscriber', loc='right');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');

Insights Gained During Multivariate Exploration¶

  • Subscribers spends lesser time on trips as compared to customers on an hourly, daily and monthly basis with average time of about 10 minutes while customers spend an average of about 25 minutes on trips.
  • Based on the heatmap above we can observe that during the weekends customers seems to be most users in demand for bikes with a concentration time around 10AM to 6PM while during weekdays subscribers seems to be the most in demand for bike at a conecentration time around 7AM to 9AM and 4PM to 6PM

<a = id='conclusions'></a>

Conclusions¶

  • Subscribers are the major users of the Ford Gobike System, they use to mostly commute to their workplace on weekdays. While Customers spend longer duration of time on trips probably for recreation,visitation,fun places and all sort.
  • The 'BikeShare For All ' program is a comprehensive bike share equity program, which includes equitable station siting, outreach, and discounted pricing to help expand transportation access to underserved communities. Only people registered to this program can use it, customers pay based on time spent on each trip that's why there was no count for customers using the 'BikeShare For All ' program
  • Market St at 10th St station is the most popular station in terms of demand for bikes with close to 12,000 trips in the first quarter, it is located in a neighbourhood of Civic center and in a city of San Francisco, San Francisco seems to be the major city were Ford Gobike system is used with atleast 72% of the total trips of the Ford Gobike system in the city.
  • Customers travel a farther distance from the start station than subscribers.
  • During the weekends customers seems to be most users in demand for bikes with a concentration time around 10AM to 6PM while during weekdays subscribers seems to be the most in demand for bike at a conecentration time around 7AM to 9AM and 4PM to 6PM
